# Unity Project Conventions

## Runtime
- Unity 6 (6000.x) with URP 17.3.0
- New Input System (`com.unity.inputsystem` 1.18.0) — never use legacy `Input.GetKey` in new code
- KCP is the **primary** network transport (connects to Go server via `NanoKcpClient`)
- Netcode for GameObjects package is installed but **not used** at runtime — do not inherit `NetworkBehaviour`

## Coding Standards
- One class per file, filename matches class name
- No namespace for gameplay scripts (global namespace matches Unity convention for small projects)
- Use `[SerializeField]` for inspector-exposed private fields; avoid public fields except for quick prototyping
- Shared utilities go in `AnimatorUtils` / `GameConstants` static classes
- Magic numbers belong in `GameConstants.cs`

## Component Patterns
- Local player: `SimpleThirdPersonController` (MonoBehaviour) — handles input, movement, animation, and KCP sync
- Remote player: `RemotePlayerController` — interpolates server-pushed position/rotation
- Network: `NanoKcpClient` → `NetworkPlayerManager` routes push messages to spawn/update remote players
- Enemy: `EnemyAI` supports both `isLocalAuthority` (local AI) and remote sync via `ApplyNetworkState()`

## Key Files
- `GameConstants.cs` — spawn position, speeds, sync interval, network defaults
- `AnimatorUtils.cs` — shared animator parameter check
- `NanoKcpClient.cs` — KCP client with auto-reconnect and reqId-based response callbacks
- `NightmareSceneSetup.cs` (Editor) — one-click scene setup tool under `TraeTools` menu

## Debug Keys (Editor/DevBuild only, wrapped in `#if DEVELOPMENT_BUILD || UNITY_EDITOR`)
- `K` — fly up (SimpleThirdPersonController)
- `J` — force attack (PlayerAttack)
- `8` — play Dead animation
- `9` — play Dance animation
